    "body": "### Problem\n\n`MAX_TIMEOUT` is defined in `share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/_system.lua` on line 82 as `local MAX_TIMEOUT = 2 ^ 31`.\n\nOn 32-bit systems this is bigger than the max signed value which is `2 ^ 31 - 1` and as a result when calling wait without an argument (like `vim.system(cmd):wait()`) this default is used, but because it overflows it is interpreted as the lowest possible 32-bit negative value and I get a traceback:\n\n```\nE5108: Error executing lua /home/dan/.neovim/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/_system.lua:89: timeout must be >= 0\nstack traceback:\n        [C]: in function 'wait'\n        /home/dan/.neovim/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/_system.lua:89: in function 'wait'\n        [string \":lua\"]:1: in main chunk\n```\n\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nType \n\n```:lua vim.system({\"ls\"}):wait()```\n\non a 32-bit system.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI would expect no traceback. The way to fix this is to define `MAX_TIMEOUT` as `2 ^ 31 - 1`.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.0-dev-1383+g02bc40c194\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nprobably not. they don't have lua\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux Debian unstable\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.14.0-dev (8dfd2e56)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuilt from repo",
